<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Aean on 04-23-2001 08:26 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I am an officer in my guild and surprisingly alot of people listen to what I have to say :) (quite in the peanut gallery) and when it comes to people in the guild this is my take on it. In real life we do not judge our friends by the jobs they do nor the proficiency in which they do it so why would I judge my EQ friends that way as well. Any monkey can push buttons to get to level 60, but it's your friends that make the game and it's because of my friends that I have even played this long. Equipment I view in the same way, I'm not friends with someone because they have a fast car, the one they have gets the job done and as long as they are happy it's all that matters. If I happen to get something in game that they can use it's theirs no questions asked no payment wanted because their friendship means more to me than 1's and 0's. 

Eventually a new game will come out and no one will remember what PH@T L33WTZ you had. They will remember that time in befallen when you were all level 15, or that time in Splitpaw where you got the heal off just in time to save the tank. Your first dragon raid, that newbie you helped out to buy spells who remembered you and said hi 30 levels later, that whacky cleric from the boards who swore by his hand to hand skills :) When all is said and done and the last person has logged off of everquest and the servers are shut down and all your uber equipment is gone for good the only thing you will be remembered for, is you and how you treated everyone else.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
